snippet.title: Amber Heard to join forces with Cherie Blair to campaign for the unfairly jailed - Today News
snippet.description:
Thanks for watching my video. 
If you like my videos, please subscribe to the channel to receive the latest videos 
Videos can use content-based copyright law contains reasonable use Fair Use (https://www.youtube.com/yt/copyright/). 
For any copyright, please send me a message.   Hollywood actress Amber Heard is joining forces with former Prime Minister's wife Cherie Blair to campaign against people being unfairly jailed.  The film star, who has traded domestic abuse allegations with ex-husband Johnny Depp, which both deny, will speak on the same stage as human rights QC Mrs Blair at the United Nations.  Aqauman star Heard, 33, is a United Nations ambassador on human rights.  She and Mrs Blair will speak at the UN General Assembly in New York next week to highlight the case of a Russian-born businesswoman, Marsha Lazareva, who was held in a Kuwaiti prison for 470 days.  Ms Lazareva was sentenced to 10 years' jail with hard labour after being found guilty of embezzlement by a Kuwait court last year.   Supporters claim Ms Lazareva was incarcerated in a “show trial” over a major port investment.  Prosecutors accused her of embezzling money but, according to her allies, it was in fact frozen in the United Arab Emirates and has since been released to all investors.   Her supporters have also complained about her treatment at the hands of the Kuwaiti authorities while she was held.  Mrs Blair, who lived in Downing Street from 1997 to 2007, said: “Arbitrary detention continues to be ignored.  “I will highlight the Marsha Lazareva case, but international law is flouted the world over and the international community must do more to tackle this outrage.”

snippet.title: RUSSIA: AUTHORITIES CRACK DOWN ON AMBER SMUGGLING
snippet.description:
(30 Nov 1995) Russian/Nat

The authorities in Russia are cracking down on amber smuggling. 

Hundreds of tons of amber are coming into the country illegally from the Russian enclave of Kaliningrad on the Baltic coast.

Ninety per cent of the world's amber supply comes from the Baltic shores -- and all it takes to collect the precious gems is a water jet and a shovel.

Kaliningrad -- once controlled by the Nazis -- is now Russia's main source of amber.

The naval outpost on the Baltic coast has huge reserves of the golden gem.

But economic hardship and flourishing crime mean that much of it is smuggled illegally into Russia.

While an estimated 650 tons a year is delivered to the factory in the town of Amber -- at least 300 tons is smuggled illegally over the border to mainland Russia. 

SOUNDBITE: (Russian)
Interests of the state should be upheld. But they can be upheld through various means and our proposal is that the state should reserve the right to own minerals separated from rock mass.
SUPER CAPTION:  Aleksei Khan, director amber factory

Hundreds of people, left unemployed by cutbacks in military spending after the end of the Cold War, now survive by digging for the material.  

They earn around 20 to 30 U-S dollars per day. 

That's a small fortune compared with the average Russian monthly salary of 100 USD. 

But the job is hazardous. 

The local Interior Ministry department makes regular raids on the amber fields, confiscating equipment and forcing the diggers to fill in the deep holes they have dug. 

SOUNDBITE: (Russian)
There are fences who will pay good money for the amber, but the majority of the diggers just do it to get some money to buy vodka. But with all this digging people can die in mud slides. Last summer we found the body of a fourteen-year old.
SUPER CAPTION: Lt Pyotr Ivankov, Kaliningrad police

But local crime officials say the punishments are ineffective. 

The most these men will receive is a heavy fine. They'll probably be back again tomorrow -- searching for amber to pay the fine.

snippet.title: Kaliningrad’s Amber Mines Are Producing Record-Breaking Exquisite and Expensive “Sunny Stones”
snippet.description:
Subscribe to Vesti News https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCa8MaD6gQscto_Nq1i49iew?sub_confirmation=1
A record amount of amber has been mined in the Kaliningrad Region: 450 tons of this semiprecious stone for the first time in more than 40 years. The previous record is exceeded by 30%. The biggest stones will take their places in museums. Smaller ones will be used to plot special amber routes for the coming 2018 World Cup.
